<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-04-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-04-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="169" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                            <head>No. 169.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward
                                        Thornton</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-04-05"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 5,
                                        1872</date>. (Received April 9.)</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                                receipt of your letter of the 29th ultimo, relative to the facts
                                which I was instructed by Lord Granville to submit to you, with
                                regard to the slave-trade on the east coast of Africa, and I beg to
                                offer you my best thanks for having acceded to the wishes of Her
                                Majesty’s government in this matter. I have forwarded a copy of your
                                note to Lord Granville, to whom I hope it will be satisfactory.</p>
                            <p>I have, &amp;c,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>EDWD. THORNTON.</signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>